on Bond Fine Hunter or at car shows or in junkyards or anywhere because there's just not that many around.

Eight years.

Really?

You gonna restore it?

I just pulled it apart, checked the clearance on the rings, did a little filing and sanding, cleaned it up, put new rings and put it back together.
So is this like working on a Volkswagen?
Very similar.
Yeah, it's got jugs and liners and kind of.
Yeah, it's pretty cool.

No.

Something similar to that.

Yes.
No park.

I believe reverse is all the way up.
Reverse all the way up.

Oh, okay.
That's the shifting mechanism.
So adjust your parking gear or parking brake, boys and girls.
Yeah, really, no kidding.
So you have a big family.
You told me you have how many kids?
Well, can you fit 10 in there?
Still six at home.

Yes.

the drip rail down that hole side.

The number's gone.

Finishing up the engine?
Yeah.

Rebuild the carburetors.

Three bolts?
Three bolts.
No kidding.

But the engine transmission together goes up?
Transaxle.
Yep.
All together.
Yeah, the neatest thing I like about this van over Volkswagen bus or even minivans nowadays
Both back windows, not the quarter windows, but both back windows roll all the way down.
Well, thank you, sir.
Thanks for sharing your little pride and joy.
When we got here, asked everybody we could, who are the car guys at Tad?
Who can we talk to?
And we got this guy's name several times, Kyle.
Kyle owns a street rod shop in St.
George and builds amazing things, like this chopped 39 Lincoln two-door fastback, which is just killer.
We asked Kyle to tell us about
This Buick he's standing in front of here.
And by the way, thanks for taking your time off.
You're not making $100 an hour while we're here just talking to you.
So why is this an interesting car?
You know, this car is one family owned.
My landlord, his grandfather, went to Detroit with his daughter, which is my landlord's mother.
He wanted to pick this car up with zero miles.
He didn't want it to come on a transport.
He wanted to pick up the car with zero miles on it from the factory.
He wanted to roll off the assembly line into his hands with the options he wanted.

and he actually did it and what year 50 this is a 57 buick roadmaster the different things that are on this car is the one piece back window which a lot of these were the three piece because it's a one piece back window and because it's a no post hard top this actually comes with an inch and three quarter chop compared to like the special which is pretty cool and
I think with the four-door it actually helps because the car seems a little unbalanced in a two-door.
It doesn't seem quite long enough but you know whatever it would have been we would have still been restoring it because
It's their car.
So it's never been out of the family.
Did he order it from a local Buick dealership?
I don't know on that, but I did check into it and all I know is that he went to Salt Lake, got on a train with his daughter, they went to Detroit,
She wrote a diary on the whole trip.
And so there's a diary on the whole trip of the car going to get it.
And he went to Detroit, straight to Detroit, went to the factory, did get it right off the assembly line.
And so they drove it back and that was their family car forever and ever and ever until...
When did it come off the road?
Do you have any idea?
There was actually an engine fire that actually stopped this one.
It took most of the paint off the passenger side fender, some of the hood.
So it sat in the backyard then?
Yeah, it actually sat behind this shop.
Oh, because he owns the building.
So this car really has been in this one town its whole life.
Yes, very much so.
And you showed us a picture over there.
Yeah, it's in front of my landlord's grandfather's favorite restaurant, Dick's Cafe, which was here on St.
George Boulevard.
And it's on the original chassis?
Yes, most of it is the original chassis.

but the original motor with the original heads, still basically a numbers matching.
So the color scheme, tell me how it's going to work.
So the mint green is kind of, it is the original color, but we were doing it in a satin.
The whole build has been a practical build.
You know, there's nothing that we spent a lot of money on here.

I want to start with shaking your hand, Dave, thank you, for agreeing to meet with us today after your day job.
My pleasure.
And tell us about a car that I'm totally intrigued with.
It's kind of a unique car.
It's an Atlas, actually.
It's not an Allied, but it's a very early version.
This was a splash mold taken off of a Cisitalia.
Piero Truffi dominated the Le Mans race in, what, 40s?
with a car like this, and Pete Peterson bought one of the 12 that Pierre Truffy... This is Pete Peterson, Robert Peterson, Robert Peterson Publishing, Hot Rod Magazine.
Right, exactly.
So we don't know if it was voluntary or just something that...
The guys just did, but they took a splash mold off of this car.
There's actually one of the cars that's in the Museum of Modern Art in New York, and it's still there and it's still beautiful.
In 51, this was chosen by curators of the Museum of Modern Art to be one of the eight most beautiful cars in the world.
It really is.
It has just beautiful lines, very classic lines.
So they took a splash mold off of it, and then they said, hey, maybe we could start building these cars.
And so we don't know who actually built the frame.
We think that the guy that later raced it at Bonneville built this frame.
But it's made out of elliptical tubing that was the struts for the World War II gliders, the troop gliders.
And so if you look at this elliptical tubing that builds the frame, it's very, very strong, very, very light.
And they have, these are torsion bars.
They come back to arms here.

And then if you look back here to the rear end, this is a Ford banjo style rear end, but they took the drive shafts that would normally be up there by the transmission, and they scabbed them onto the sides of this banjo rear end to make a swing axle rear end.
So do you have any idea who built this chassis?
I think it was, I'm sorry I forget the guy's name.
It starts with an H, Herzog or something like that that built it.
They did the same thing up front.
It's basically a solid front axle, only they broke it in the middle and put big ball joints in the big tie rod ends.
So it's a swing axle.
So the car's unloaded right now.
There's not much weight on it right now, so all the wheels are kind of cambered under.
But it's fully adjustable.
It's got a torsion bar front and rear.
Kind of a long...
Long way to go to get their steering from the center.
But they put it in the centers because they didn't want to have a lot of bumps there as it went through the suspension cycles.
Originally it had a Duesenberg straight eight engine that they'd cut in half to make a four-cylinder double overhead cam engine.
They had to make a billet crank
in order to make this work.
And so they ran that a little bit and they had some issues, as you can imagine.
And then later on went to a flathead when they did one sports car race with the flathead.
And so that's what we got it.
We got it with a flathead in it.

Jeff Hacker, yeah.

we thought it was very similar to ours, and the more we did the research, the more we found out that that was actually this car.
